The JVDT-7 System: A Complete Compendium
Core Principles, Developmental Frameworks, Diagnostic Tools, and Facilitation Guides
This document outlines the complete architecture of the JVDT-7 system, a 7-axis model of cognitive and moral development designed to map the journey from knowledge to wisdom.
Part 1: The Core Philosophy & First Principles
A. The Two Guiding Formulas
	‚Ä¢	The Knowledge Formula: Information + Integration = Knowledge
	‚Ä¢	The Wisdom Formula: Knowledge + Practice = Wisdom
B. The Three Core Values
The system's moral framework is guided by three core values, with the third emerging from the balance of the first two:
	‚Ä¢	Love (Compassion, Empathy, Mercy)
	‚Ä¢	Respect (Justice, Fairness, Principle)
	‚Ä¢	Happiness (Joy, Peace, Harmony) - The resulting equilibrium.
C. The Seven Axes of Development
The JVDT-7 model is built on seven developmental axes, each representing a core faculty of conscience and cognition.
	‚Ä¢	Perception (A ‚Üî N): Associative vs. Analytical
	‚Ä¢	Interpretation (R ‚Üî C): Root vs. Context
	‚Ä¢	Reflection (I ‚Üî E): Internal vs. External
	‚Ä¢	Application (D ‚Üî P): Idealistic vs. Pragmatic
	‚Ä¢	Motivation (S ‚Üî M): Self-Directed vs. Mutual-Directed
	‚Ä¢	Orientation (T ‚Üî H): Temporal vs. Holistic
	‚Ä¢	Value Expression (L ‚Üî R): Love vs. Respect
D. First Principles: 10 Core Theses
	‚Ä¢	Personhood before profile. JVDT-7 maps faculties of conscience and cognition; it does not fix identity.
	‚Ä¢	Knowing is moral. Epistemology and ethics are inseparable: knowledge tends toward good via practice.
	‚Ä¢	Two equations govern growth. Information + Integration = Knowledge; Knowledge + Practice = Wisdom.
	‚Ä¢	Seven faculties. Perception, Interpretation, Reflection, Application, Motivation, Orientation, Value Expression.
	‚Ä¢	Virtue formation. Each axis matures through habits (arete), not mere preference.
	‚Ä¢	Developmental trajectory. Learners move from novice ‚Üí competent ‚Üí proficient ‚Üí expert ‚Üí wise.
	‚Ä¢	Dialectical pairs. Every axis is a tension that should be harmonized, not ‚Äúwon.‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Context matters. Classrooms and communities bias axes; design must counterbalance, not amplify bias.
	‚Ä¢	Telemetry over taxonomy. Types are snapshots; growth vectors are the point.
	‚Ä¢	Christ-shaped telos. For this system: Love, Respect, and Joy (Happiness) crown wisdom.
Part 2: The JVDT-7 Axis Deep Dives
Detailed breakdown of each axis, its theoretical anchors, and its developmental path.
1) PERCEPTION ‚Äî A ‚Üî N (Association ‚Üî Analysis)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: How awareness first takes hold of reality (pattern/analogy vs. structure/evidence).
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: Aristotle (aisthesis & nous), Augustine (illumination, love shapes sight).
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Jung (intuition vs. sensing), Polanyi (tacit knowledge), Kahneman (System 1/2).
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	A-virtue: Attunement; shadow: credulity, over-reading.
	‚Ä¢	N-virtue: Clarity; shadow: reductionism, coldness.
	‚Ä¢	Development: Novice over-relies on one pole; expert can switch lenses on demand.
	‚Ä¢	Signals: A-leaners recall stories; N-leaners ask for definitions and rubrics.
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Dual-entry notes (story ‚Üî schema), evidence logs, analogy drills, counter-example hunts.
2) INTERPRETATION ‚Äî R ‚Üî C (Root ‚Üî Context)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: Where meaning anchors (first principles) vs. situates (systems, ecology).
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: Aquinas (principia; causes), Augustine (order of loves).
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Vygotsky (context; mediation), Bronfenbrenner (ecological systems), Systems thinking.
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	R-virtue: Fidelity; shadow: rigidity, anachronism.
	‚Ä¢	C-virtue: Relevance; shadow: relativism, drift.
	‚Ä¢	Development: From either/or to rooted relevance.
	‚Ä¢	Signals: R-questions ‚ÄúWhere does this come from?‚Äù; C-questions ‚ÄúWhat does it depend on?‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Origin tracing, timeline + map overlays, transfer tasks across contexts.
3) REFLECTION ‚Äî I ‚Üî E (Internal ‚Üî External)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: How comprehension is consolidated: solitude/synthesis vs. dialogue/teaching.
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: monastic meditatio vs. proclamation.
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Socratic method, Metacognition (Flavell), Articulation in cognitive apprenticeship.
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	I-virtue: Depth; shadow: rumination, isolation.
	‚Ä¢	E-virtue: Sharpening; shadow: performative shallows.
	‚Ä¢	Development: Deliberate cycles of think ‚Üí speak ‚Üí refine ‚Üí rest.
	‚Ä¢	Signals: I-learners excel on journals; E-learners bloom in seminars.
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Think-write-pair-share, oral rehearsal before writing, reflection prompts keyed to errors.
4) APPLICATION ‚Äî D ‚Üî P (Idealistic ‚Üî Pragmatic)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: Turning knowing into doing: transformation/mission vs. function/execution.
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: James (faith/works); Aristotle (techne ‚Üí phronesis).
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Dreyfus model (novice‚Üíexpert), Design thinking (ideate‚Üítest).
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	D-virtue: Vision; shadow: abstraction without fruit.
	‚Ä¢	P-virtue: Reliability; shadow: myopia, box-checking.
	‚Ä¢	Development: Prototype ‚Üí feedback ‚Üí iteration ‚Üí stewardship.
	‚Ä¢	Signals: D talks outcomes for people; P talks KPIs and checklists.
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Impact hypotheses, pilot labs, pre-mortems, A/B practice logs.
5) MOTIVATION ‚Äî S ‚Üî M (Self-Directed ‚Üî Mutual-Directed)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: Why we pursue wisdom: autonomy/mastery vs. service/belonging.
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: Augustine (ordered loves); Rule of St. Benedict (obedience/community).
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Self-Determination Theory (autonomy/relatedness), Purpose research (Damon).
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	S-virtue: Ownership; shadow: ego, isolation.
	‚Ä¢	M-virtue: Contribution; shadow: conformity, people-pleasing.
	‚Ä¢	Development: Owned service ‚Äî self given for others.
	‚Ä¢	Signals: S sets personal OKRs; M thrives in peer tasks.
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Role charters, ‚Äúwho benefits?‚Äù reflections, service-learning cycles, peer gratitude rituals.
6) ORIENTATION ‚Äî T ‚Üî H (Temporal ‚Üî Holistic)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: Time-horizon and frame: near-term milestones vs. long arc and interconnection.
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: chronos vs. kairos; Proverbs (ant/sage).
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Executive function, Futures thinking, Systems causality.
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	T-virtue: Discipline; shadow: hustle tunnel.
	‚Ä¢	H-virtue: Perspective; shadow: vagueness, deferral.
	‚Ä¢	Development: Integrate cadence (T) with calling (H).
	‚Ä¢	Signals: T loves sprints; H asks ‚Äúto what end?‚Äù
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Dual-plan (90-day + 3-year), consequence mapping, weekly examen (progress + purpose).
7) VALUE EXPRESSION ‚Äî L ‚Üî R (‚Üî H balance)
	‚Ä¢	Essence: How moral energy is embodied: compassion/mercy vs. justice/standards ‚Üí joy as equilibrium.
	‚Ä¢	Anchors:
	‚Ä¢	Classical: Great Commandment; Micah 6:8 (justice, mercy, humility).
	‚Ä¢	Modern: Care ethics (Gilligan) + Justice ethics (Kohlberg).
	‚Ä¢	Virtue & Shadow:
	‚Ä¢	L-virtue: Mercy; shadow: permissiveness.
	‚Ä¢	R-virtue: Fairness; shadow: harshness.
	‚Ä¢	H-balance: Joy/shalom.
	‚Ä¢	Development: Hold standards and people together.
	‚Ä¢	Signals: L protects relationships; R protects norms.
	‚Ä¢	Practices: Restorative conferencing, transparent rubrics, gratitude & celebration cadence.
Part 3: The JVDT-7 Virtue Ladders (Rubrics)
This is the 5-stage developmental rubric for each axis, detailing the path from unconscious reaction to moralized wisdom.
Ladder 1: PERCEPTION (A ‚Üî N)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Reacts to impressions or facts without structure.
Noticing things but unable to explain why they matter.
Awareness
Recognises preference for story (A) or data (N).
Says, ‚ÄúI remember the story‚Äù / ‚ÄúI want the numbers.‚Äù
Balance
Consciously alternates between pattern and proof.
Uses both examples and evidence to justify answers.
Mastery
Integrates empathy and logic seamlessly.
Builds coherent arguments that connect people and principles.
Wisdom
Perceives truth in both image and order.
Reads situations intuitively, then articulates them analytically.
Ladder 2: INTERPRETATION (R ‚Üî C)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Accepts ideas at face value.
Repeats what is taught without questioning source or relevance.
Awareness
Begins to ask ‚ÄúWhere?‚Äù or ‚ÄúWhen?‚Äù
Seeks origin (R) or setting (C) but not both.
Balance
Connects heritage to situation.
Links cause with effect, past with present.
Mastery
Grounds context in principle.
Applies old truths to new problems with accuracy.
Wisdom
Lives ‚Äúrooted relevance.‚Äù
Preserves essence while adapting form for others‚Äô good.
Ladder 3: REFLECTION (I ‚Üî E)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Consumes information passively.
Finishes work but can‚Äôt explain thinking.
Awareness
Recognises need to process.
Begins journaling (I) or discussion (E).
Balance
Moves between solitude and sharing.
Drafts privately, then seeks feedback.
Mastery
Uses reflection to refine comprehension.
Turns dialogue into insight; insight into clear expression.
Wisdom
Models metacognition for others.
Invites others into learning loops that deepen all participants.
Ladder 4: APPLICATION (D ‚Üî P)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Acts impulsively or mechanically.
Jumps into tasks or just ‚Äúcompletes‚Äù them.
Awareness
Notices motive behind action.
Says, ‚ÄúI did this because‚Ä¶‚Äù
Balance
Links purpose and process.
Plans with vision (D) and checkpoints (P).
Mastery
Executes vision reliably.
Designs sustainable systems that serve ideals.
Wisdom
Translates ideals into cultures.
Inspires others to act with integrity and excellence.
Ladder 5: MOTIVATION (S ‚Üî M)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Works for reward or approval.
‚ÄúDid I do it right?‚Äù
Awareness
Notices internal or social drive.
Sets goals (S) or seeks belonging (M).
Balance
Owns learning and contribution.
Finishes tasks and helps peers succeed.
Mastery
Serves through strength.
Leads by example; offers expertise freely.
Wisdom
Lives vocation as service.
Finds joy where personal calling meets others‚Äô needs.
Ladder 6: ORIENTATION (T ‚Üî H)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Drifts in time‚Äîeither rushed (T) or vague (H).
Misses deadlines or over-plans ideals.
Awareness
Notices time bias.
Says, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm deadline-driven‚Äù or ‚ÄúI need space to see the whole.‚Äù
Balance
Blends schedule with story.
Keeps short-term goals aligned with long-term meaning.
Mastery
Manages seasons wisely.
Adjusts rhythm to purpose; mentors others in pacing.
Wisdom
Lives kairos inside chronos.
Turns each moment into participation in the eternal.
Ladder 7: VALUE EXPRESSION (L ‚Üî R ‚Üî H)
Stage
Description
Observable Behaviours
Instinct
Reacts emotionally or rigidly.
Over-comforts or over-corrects peers.
Awareness
Recognises bias toward mercy (L) or justice (R).
Admits, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm too soft/hard sometimes.‚Äù
Balance
Holds care and fairness together.
Mediates conflict respectfully.
Mastery
Creates restorative environments.
Upholds standards with warmth.
Wisdom
Radiates joy (H).
Relationships and systems flourish in peace and gratitude.
